CatDescriptText: Patrice Warmus, housewife, Oakland and Blanche Moska, medical secretary, East Pittsburgh, were part of the Pittsburghers Speak Up column published in the Pittsburgh Courier Newspaper, April 9, 1960, pg. 29 with question "Do you believe the moral standards of our community have deteriorated since World War II?"  Mrs. Warmus' answer reads: "In some ways they have.  There's quite a lot of juvenile delinquency which could be prevented if parents showed any interest in their children."  Ms. Moska's answer reads: "I think they have improved..."
TitMainTitle: Two frames: Portrait of Patrice Warmus wearing light colored ruffled blouse, standing with child on sidewalk in front of intersection, Downtown; Portrait of Blanche Moska wearing cats eyes eyeglasses and dark coat with circular swirled button trim, standing on sidewalk, downtown
